{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01HQpXrHcVjRoBeERz3vBzTf","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The ray-client pod is trying to connect using `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')`, but it's looking for a local `node_ip_address.json` file. This suggests the ray-client is not in \"driver\" mode connecting to a remote cluster, but rather it's trying to start a local Ray instance.\n\nLooking at the error more carefully: `ValueError: Can't find a node_ip_address.json file from /tmp/ray/session_2026-06-24_02-16-22_216732_13`. \n\nThe session appears to be from the same time as the ray-client was started. \n\nIt seems like the ray-client might already have a Ray instance running locally, which is interfering with the connection to the remote cluster. The issue is that when connecting to an existing Ray cluster via `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')`, the client shouldn't need to find a local `node_ip_address.json` file—that's typically only needed for local Ray instances. This could be a version compatibility issue with the Ray client, or there's a stale session from a previous run that's causing problems. might not be compatible with the version running in the ray-client pod. The error about the missing `node_ip_address.json` file suggests Ray is trying to initialize a local cluster instead of connecting to the existing one, which could mean the address format isn't being recognized properly or there's a version mismatch in how Ray handles remote connections. before the command ran at `02:16:30`. So something has already started Ray on the ray-client pod.\n\nLooking at the log more carefully, Ray is trying to connect to the cluster at ray-head:6379, but it's failing because it can't find the `node_ip_address.json` file. This file gets created by the local raylet when the driver starts some local processes to connect to a remote cluster. So the ray-client pod probably needs to have `ray start` runni