{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01ALfScbAtRtRXwaf4ejA3bF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good, TCP connectivity is fine. So the issue is that `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')` starts a local raylet on the ray-client pod, and that raylet is failing to start.\n\nLet me check if there's a way to get more details about why the local raylet is failing. Let me try running `ray.init` with more verbose logging and see what happens.\n\nActually, in Ray 2.9.0, to connect to a remote cluster without starting local processes, one would typically use the Ray Client protocol: `ray.init(\"ray://ray-head:10001\")`. But the validation command uses `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')`.\nThe validation command is fixed, so I need to make sure the ray-client pod can successfully run that initialization. I can't pre-start ray as a side process since the validation is a single command. Maybe the ray-head needs to expose additional ports for the raylet communication.\n\nActually, I'm realizing that in Ray 2.x, when a driver calls `ray.init(address='head:6379')`, it doesn't start a local raylet—the driver itself isn't a worker node. That `node_ip_address.json` error might be coming from something else. Let me trace through what's actually happening in the Ray source code when the driver tries to connect.\n\nThe function that waits for `node_ip_address.json` is called during `Node.__init__`, and that file only gets created once the raylet starts up. If the file doesn't exist after the timeout, it means the raylet either never started or failed to start. So the local raylet is being attempted, and something's preventing it from running—could be missing capabilities in the container, a syscall failure, or a missing binary. I should check whether the ray-client pod is using the same Ray image as the head node.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens"