{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Dn1YAjHkfnMwY7vewrKBNF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"All pods are on the same node `karma-2-control-plane`. Both ray-client and ray-head are on this node, so they share the same node filesystem (but each has its own container filesystem).\n\nWait, but the earlier check showed that BOTH ray-client and ray-head pods have the SAME `/tmp/ray/session_2026-06-24_02-16-22_216732_13` directory. This means `/tmp/ray/` is SHARED between the pods - probably through a hostPath volume or because kind containers share a common overlay filesystem for `/tmp`.\n\nActually in kind, the \"node\" (`karma-2-control-plane`) is a Docker container. \n\nHold on, looking at the inode numbers more carefully - the head pod shows `25690328` for the session directory while the client shows `25694398` for the same path. Those are different inodes, which means they're actually looking at separate filesystems, not a shared one. Each pod has its own isolated `/tmp/ray/` directory.\n\nSo when the client runs `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')`, it's not creating a new session - it's connecting to the existing cluster and the GCS tells it to use the cluster's session name. That's why both pods end up with `session_2026-06-24_02-16-22_216732_13` even though they have completely separate `/tmp` directories. The client needs its own local `node_ip_address.json` file to work with that session.\n\nLooking at what's actually in each session directory, the client's is basically empty - just an `old/` subdirectory in logs but no actual log files, no sockets, nothing. The head's session has everything: full logs, socket files for the raylet and plasma store. This tells me the local raylet on the client side never actually started. The session directory was created when `ray.init()` ran, but no local processes spun up.\n\nIn Ray 2.9.0, when you call `ray.init(address='ip:port')`, it should create the session directory and then start a local raylet process, but that's not happening here.\n\nThe raylet is a native binary, so if it fails to start - missing libraries, permission issues, whatever - there wouldn't be any logs to show what went wrong. But wait, the head pod successfully started its raylet using the same image, so the binary should work fine on the client too.\n\nLet me try running `ray start --address=ray-head:6379` directly on the client pod to see what error actually comes up. Or maybe I'm overcomplicating this - when `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')` gets called on the client, it creates the session directory but then something prevents the local raylet from starting.\n\nActually, I think I found it. The lock file `node_ip_address.json.lock` is still sitting there from the previous failed run, and when I try to initialize again, Ray sees this lock file and assumes the session is already in progress, but there's no actual `node_ip_address.json` file to go with it. That's the deadlock.\n\nThe lock file itself should release if the process dies, but something's preventing a clean recovery. I should just delete the entire `/tmp/ray/` directory on the client pod to start completely fresh.\n\nActually, let me try running `ray start --address=ray-head:6379` directly on the client pod to see what specific error we're hitting with the local raylet startup.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1349,"cache_read_input_tokens":47965,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1349},"output_tokens":43,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a55ed7b0-b053-4d12-94e1-bfbf0057a173","uuid":"1aa68f78-9590-46fd-91e6-c8ec536f9a85","request_id":"req_011CcMqbHvZ6yk1aE5LpVTp7"}
